options gen2
// MOCKUP — aspirational API for dasSQLITE rework.
// Refreshed 2026-05-04 to reflect the 12-scenario walk locks in
// ../API_MIGRATION.md. Design artifact, not yet compilable.
//
// Tutorial 32: up-only versioned schema migrations + struct-to-struct
// rebuild for SQLite-ALTER-impossible changes.
//
// SCOPE STATEMENT (first line of the tutorial prose):
//
//   Migrations are one of the biggest topics in database tooling.
//   Alembic, EF Core Migrations, Flyway, Liquibase, Rails AR,
//   Diesel, sqitch — every serious DB library has a dedicated
//   sub-project for it. Writing that story for daslang is far
//   out of scope for v1. This tutorial ships the MVP: versioned
//   up-only migrations with raw SQL and typed daslang APIs inside,
//   tracked in a `__schema_version` table, run by a single driver
//   function. Plus a struct-to-struct converter macro that turns
//   the SQLite 12-step rebuild pattern into a 10-line migration
//   body. That is ENOUGH to make dasSQLITE honest for production —
//   schema evolution is tracked, transactional, and repeatable.
//   The DEFERRED list at the bottom names what we explicitly
//   don't ship and what to do instead.
//
// SEPARATE MODULE: `daslib/sqlite_migrate`. Users who don't need
// migrations don't `require` it. The migration symbols never
// appear in their namespace.

require daslib/sql
require daslib/sqlite_migrate
require sqlite/sqlite_boost
require daslib/result
require daslib/option
require strings

// ======================================================================
// PART 1 — Define a schema and write a few migrations
// ======================================================================
//
// The struct describes the CURRENT schema. Migrations describe the
// PATH from prior states. Once shipped, a migration is FROZEN — to
// change anything, write a new one with a higher version number.

[sql_table(name="users")]
struct User {
    @sql_primary_key Id : int
    Name  : string
    Email : string                     // added in migration 2
    Score : int = 0                    // added in migration 4 with default
}

// --- migration 1: bootstrap ------------------------------------------
//
// Annotation parameters:
//   version=N           required
//   description=…       optional; appears in __schema_version + logs
//   vacuum=true         optional; runs `VACUUM` after this call commits
//   analyze=true        optional; runs `ANALYZE` after this call commits
//
// Body uses raw SQL because at v=1 the struct's *current* shape
// (Id, Name, Email, Score) doesn't match v=1's schema (Id, Name).
// Migrations always reference prior schemas via raw SQL — daslang
// has no model-snapshot system.

[sql_migration(version=1)]
def migration_001(db : SqlRunner) {
    db |> exec("CREATE TABLE users (Id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, Name TEXT NOT NULL)")
}

// --- migration 2: add a column (typed form) --------------------------
//
// `add_column` is the typed alternative to raw ALTER TABLE … ADD COLUMN.
// It reads the field type from the current struct and emits the right
// SQL: NOT NULL when the field isn't `Option<T>`, NULL when it is,
// DEFAULT clause from the `default=` argument or struct-level default.

[sql_migration(version=2, description="add email column")]
def migration_002(db : SqlRunner) {
    db |> add_column(type<User>, .Email, default = "")
    // emits: ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN Email TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT ''
}

// --- migration 3: index + backfill -----------------------------------
//
// A migration body is just a daslang function — multiple statements,
// mixed APIs (raw exec, typed DDL, typed DML, _sql chains), arbitrary
// daslang control flow. All statements run inside one transaction;
// any failure rolls everything back.

[sql_migration(version=3, description="index email; backfill unknowns",
               analyze=true)]                  // refresh stats after CREATE INDEX
def migration_003(db : SqlRunner) {
    db |> create_index(type<User>, fields = (.Email,))
    // emits: CREATE INDEX idx_users_email ON users(Email)
    //   (name auto-derived to match [sql_index] convention; override with `name=`)

    db |> _sql_update(type<User>,
        where = $(u) => u.Email == "",
        set   = (Email = "unknown@example.com"))
}

// --- migration 4: add a field with a struct-level default ------------

[sql_migration(version=4, description="add score column")]
def migration_004(db : SqlRunner) {
    db |> add_column(type<User>, .Score)
    // Score's default comes from the struct definition (`Score : int = 0`).
    // emits: ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN Score INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0
}

// ======================================================================
// PART 2 — App startup
// ======================================================================

[export]
def main() {
    // Preferred form: with_latest_sqlite combines with_sqlite +
    // apply_recommended_pragmas + migrate_to_latest. Less ceremony,
    // harder to ship a binary that opens the DB without bringing it
    // up to date.
    with_latest_sqlite("app.db") <| $(db) {
        // … application code runs against the latest schema …
        // The struct `User` matches the v=4 shape.
    }
}

// Equivalent explicit form (when you want inspection or non-default pragmas):
def main_explicit() {
    with_sqlite("app.db") <| $(db) {
        db |> apply_recommended_pragmas()         // sets WAL, busy_timeout=5000ms, etc.
        let n = db |> migrate_to_latest()
        to_log(LOG_INFO, "applied {n} migration(s); schema at v{db |> current_schema_version()}")
        // … app code …
    }
}

// ======================================================================
// PART 3 — Inspection (no migrations run)
// ======================================================================
//
// All three functions are pure read; they never create the audit
// table, never write a row, never run a migration. If __schema_version
// doesn't exist: current → 0, pending → all registered, history → [].

def cli_status() {
    with_sqlite("app.db") <| $(db) {
        let applied = db |> current_schema_version()
        to_log(LOG_INFO, "current: v{applied}")

        let pending = db |> pending_migrations()
        to_log(LOG_INFO, "pending: {length(pending)} migration(s)")
        for (p in pending) {
            to_log(LOG_INFO, "  v{p.version}: {p.description}")
        }

        let history = db |> migration_history()
        to_log(LOG_INFO, "history:")
        for (r in history) {
            to_log(LOG_INFO, "  v{r.version} {r.description} at {r.applied_at}")
        }
    }
}

// `try_` variant for tools / CI / deploy pipelines that want
// structured error handling instead of panic-on-failure.
def cli_upgrade() {
    with_sqlite("app.db") <| $(db) {
        match (db |> try_migrate_to_latest()) {
            if Result::Ok(n)   : to_log(LOG_INFO,  "ok, {n} applied")
            if Result::Err(e)  : to_log(LOG_ERROR, "migration FAILED: {e}")
        }
    }
}

// ======================================================================
// PART 4 — Adopting migrations on an existing DB ("baseline")
// ======================================================================
//
// You've been shipping the app without `daslib/sqlite_migrate`. Your DB
// already has tables. Now you want to start tracking migrations. You
// can either:
//
// (a) write your first migration as the first CHANGE you need to make
//     (recommended) — `migration_001` does ALTER TABLE rather than
//     CREATE TABLE; applies cleanly to the existing DB.
//
// (b) write `migration_001` as a CREATE-TABLE-shaped retroactive baseline,
//     and call `baseline()` once during adoption to mark v=1 as already
//     applied (Flyway's `baseline` pattern).
//
// Recipe for (b):

[export]
def main_with_adoption() {
    with_sqlite("app.db") <| $(db) {
        // ONE-TIME BASELINE BLOCK — remove after one release cycle once
        // every existing user has booted this binary at least once.
        if (db |> current_schema_version() == 0 && db |> table_exists("users")) {
            db |> baseline(version = 1)
            to_log(LOG_INFO, "stamped existing DB as v1 (baseline)")
        }
        db |> migrate_to_latest()
    }
}

// `baseline(db, version=N)` semantics:
//   - stamps v1..N rows in __schema_version (descriptions from
//     registered annotations where available, "[baseline]" sentinel
//     otherwise);
//   - applied_at = now (stamping time, not historical apply time);
//   - idempotent (already-stamped versions are no-ops);
//   - errors if N > registered_max (almost always a typo).
//
// LAYER-1 WARNING. If you forget the baseline block: when
// `migrate_to_latest` first creates `__schema_version` and finds
// existing user tables, it logs:
//
//   WARNING: this DB has existing tables/views/indexes but no
//   migration history (__schema_version was just created). If your
//   first migration creates tables that already exist, it will fail.
//   To adopt migrations on an existing DB, call `db |> baseline(version=N)`
//   before `migrate_to_latest()`. See tut 32 § "Adopting migrations
//   on an existing DB".
//
// LAYER-2 ENRICHED PANIC. If you ignore the warning and migration_001's
// CREATE TABLE does fail because the table already exists, the panic
// includes the same baseline hint. So a naive
// `with_sqlite → with_latest_sqlite` swap on an existing DB:
//   1. boots → warning logged;
//   2. migration_001 fails → panic with actionable hint;
//   3. user reads hint → adds baseline block → restarts → works.

// ======================================================================
// PART 5 — Schema rebuild (struct-to-struct convert)
// ======================================================================
//
// SQLite's ALTER vocabulary is narrow. Some changes require the
// 12-step rebuild: CREATE TABLE T_new with new shape, INSERT … SELECT
// from T with mapped columns, drop indexes/triggers, DROP TABLE T,
// rename T_new → T. Rather than ship a `recreate_table` runtime, we
// give you the building blocks; the rebuild is 10 lines.
//
// Suppose v=5 adds @sql_unique to Email AND renames LegacyName →
// Name. SQLite can't ALTER COLUMN ADD UNIQUE; a rebuild is needed.

[sql_table(name="users", legacy=true)]    // historical schema; readable for SELECT
struct UserV4 {                           // describes the v=4 shape
    @sql_primary_key Id : int
    LegacyName  : string
    Email : string
    Score : int
}

// `[sql_table(legacy=true)]` semantics:
//   - allows the same `name=` as a non-legacy [sql_table];
//   - readable via select_from(type<S>);
//   - excluded from current-schema registry: not eligible for
//     create_table / insert / _sql_update / _sql_delete / etc.
//     (compile error pointing at the current non-legacy struct).

// updated current struct (User above gets these extra annotations
// in real code; shown inline for clarity):
//
//   [sql_table(name="users")]
//   struct User {
//       @sql_primary_key Id : int
//       @sql_renamed_from = "LegacyName" Name : string   // rename hint
//       @sql_unique Email : string                       // new constraint
//       Score : int = 0
//   }

[sql_migration(version=5, description="rename LegacyName + unique Email")]
def migration_005(db : SqlRunner) {
    // 1. struct-to-struct converter — auto-derived where trivial,
    //    dev override block for non-trivial fields.
    let convert = struct_convert(type<UserV4>, type<User>) $(old, var new) {
        // The macro auto-fills:
        //   new.Id = old.Id
        //   new.Name = old.LegacyName     (via @sql_renamed_from hint)
        //   new.Email = old.Email
        //   new.Score = old.Score
        // Dev only writes overrides for non-trivial cases (none here).
    }

    // 2. the rebuild — 5 lines, all using existing primitives:
    db |> create_table(type<User>, name = "users_new")
    for (old in db |> select_from(type<UserV4>)) {
        var new : User = default
        convert(old, new)
        db |> insert_to(type<User>, new, name = "users_new")
    }
    db |> exec("DROP TABLE users")
    db |> exec("ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users")
    // Indexes recreate automatically via [sql_index] / @sql_unique on
    // current struct (handled by create_table). FKs recreate via
    // @sql_references annotations.
}

// `struct_convert` auto-derives:
//   - same name + same type → direct copy
//   - same name + T → Option<T> → Some(old.X)
//   - same name + INT ↔ STRING ↔ FLOAT → cast (to_string / to_int / float)
//   - new field with daslang default → uses default
//   - new Option<T> field → none()
//   - field gone from target → omitted
//   - @sql_renamed_from hint → reads from old's old name
//
// kabooms (macro_error; needs override):
//   - Option<T> → T (existing rows might be NULL)
//   - new non-Option field with no default
//   - same name + incompatible type
//   - lossy primitive conversions without confirm_lossy=true
//
// PHILOSOPHY: opt-in convenience. If you don't keep
// [sql_table(legacy=true)] historical structs, write the rebuild as
// raw INSERT … SELECT — same 4-line pattern, hand-mapped column lists.
// Both paths work; the macro is for users who prefer field-mapping
// safety over the maintenance cost of historical structs.

// ======================================================================
// PART 6 — When migrations fail
// ======================================================================
//
// Each `migrate_to_latest` call is one transaction (α-shape). All
// pending migrations + their audit inserts apply atomically. If any
// migration body fails:
//
//   - whole call rolls back; DB stays at the version it was before
//     the call;
//   - audit table unchanged (no rows for migrations attempted in
//     this call);
//   - LOG_ERROR with version + description + underlying error +
//     rolled-back list;
//   - panic message (or Result::Err for try_) includes "the DB does
//     NOT need to be reset" — fix the body and re-run.
//
// Migration bodies should be DB-only. Anything that touches the
// outside world (HTTP, file writes, system commands) is NOT rolled
// back. Re-execution doubles those side effects.
//
// FAIL-FAST. Error in migration N aborts the runner — N+1 doesn't
// run. No "skip bad migration" mode.

// ======================================================================
// PART 7 — Concurrent runners
// ======================================================================
//
// Multiple processes calling `migrate_to_latest` against the same DB
// (k8s rolling deploy, multi-worker app, dev launches twice) are
// coordinated by SQLite's RESERVED file lock — `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`
// blocks until the holder commits.
//
// `with_latest_sqlite` sets `busy_timeout = 5000ms` by default, so
// the second process waits 5 seconds for the first to finish. Past
// that, `try_migrate_to_latest` returns SQLITE_BUSY in Result::Err;
// strict form panics.
//
// CAVEAT — network filesystems. OS file locking is unreliable on
// NFS, SMB, k8s shared volumes. Don't rely on this contract for
// shared-volume deploys; run migrations as a separate explicit step
// before launching app instances.

// ======================================================================
// PART 8 — Rollback ("undo v7")
// ======================================================================
//
// dasSQLITE deliberately ships NO down-migrations and NO migrate-to-
// version. The door is closed permanently — not v1, not v2, not ever.
// Down migrations in every shipping framework are written, never run,
// and rot. Modern best practice: backup, forward-fix, restore-when-needed.
//
// FORWARD-FIX (recommended response). v7 broke things → write v8 that
// fixes it. Audit trail shows v7 ('add Score') + v8 ('correct Score
// backfill') in chronological order. Permanent record of the screwup.
//
// BACKUP-RESTORE (when forward-fix can't recover lost data). Restore
// the DB file from a backup taken before v7. If you want to skip the
// bad v7 (because v8 fixes it forward): manually
//   INSERT INTO __schema_version VALUES (7, '[manually skipped]', unixepoch());
// to mark v7 as already-applied. Operator-intervention territory.
//
// EF/Flyway comparison: `dotnet ef database update <PrevMigration>`,
// `alembic downgrade -1`, `flyway undo` — these intentionally don't
// exist here. The reasoning is in tut 32's "rollback" section.

// ======================================================================
// PART 9 — Squash (3 years in)
// ======================================================================
//
// If your project has accumulated 100+ migrations, squash old ones
// into a baseline by hand:
//   1. Pick a squash point N. Every deployed user must be past v=N.
//   2. Spin up :memory: SQLite, apply migrations 1..N, dump schema.
//   3. Hand-write a new migration_N body that emits that schema.
//   4. Delete migrations 1..(N-1) from the codebase.
//   5. Existing users' DBs already have v1..v(N-1) rows; runner is
//      a no-op for them. New users boot against the squashed
//      registry; v=N runs first.
// One-time op per squash point. Don't squash unless you need to.

// ======================================================================
// __schema_version table — auto-created on first migrate_to_latest
// ======================================================================
//
//   CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS __schema_version (
//       version     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
//       description TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
//       applied_at  INTEGER NOT NULL              -- unix epoch seconds
//   )
//
// Three columns. One row per applied migration. All rows are
// successes by construction (failures roll back atomically with the
// body). `MigrationRecord` mirrors this 1:1.
//
// PER-CALL TRANSACTION. Each `migrate_to_latest` call wraps the
// pending list in:
//     BEGIN IMMEDIATE;
//       <body of v(K+1)>; INSERT v(K+1) audit;
//       <body of v(K+2)>; INSERT v(K+2) audit;
//       …
//     COMMIT;
// Any error rolls back the whole call. After COMMIT, runner emits
// VACUUM and/or ANALYZE if any pending migration set those flags.

// ======================================================================
// DUPLICATE VERSION = COMPILE ERROR
// ======================================================================
//
// Detection is GLOBAL (program-scoped, across modules):
//
//     [sql_migration(version=2)]
//     def migration_002_a(db : SqlRunner) { … }   in app/migrations_email.das
//
//     [sql_migration(version=2)]                   in app/migrations_avatar.das
//     def migration_002_b(db : SqlRunner) { … }   // ← compile error
//
// Error names both functions AND both module paths so the dev can
// locate the conflict. Resolution: renumber the LATER-merged
// branch's migration to the next free version (gap-allowed:
// `1, 2, 3, 5, 6` is valid; renumber 2 → 4).

// ======================================================================
// DEFERRED / OUT OF SCOPE
// ======================================================================
//
// Permanent NO (design choice, not "missing in v1"):
//
// • DOWN MIGRATIONS / ROLLBACK. See Part 8 for reasoning + recipes.
// • MIGRATE-TO-VERSION (`migrate_to(db, target=N)`). Same reasoning.
//
// Withdrawn from prior deferred lists:
//
// • 12-STEP ALTER HELPER (`recreate_table`). dasSQLITE bundles SQLite
//   3.41.2; full ALTER vocabulary is available; users with non-
//   ALTERable schema changes use Part 5's struct_convert + name=
//   overload pattern instead.
//
// Future tooling (no commitment, revisit on demand):
//
// • SCHEMA AUTOGENERATE FROM STRUCT DIFF (EF's `dotnet ef migrations
//   add`). Requires a model-snapshot system. The struct_convert
//   approach in Part 5 is the daslang-native answer for the rebuild
//   half; full autogen of ALTERs would be a separate
//   `daslib/sqlite_migrate_gen` follow-up.
//
// • `daspkg sql-migrate snapshot` / `daspkg sql-migrate squash`. CLI
//   tools for snapshot-rotation and hand-squash automation. Overlap
//   significantly; ship together if/when demand surfaces.
//
// • SEMANTIC-DUPE LINT. Fuzzy detection of "two migrations with
//   suspiciously-similar bodies" via the chunk-13 detect_duplicates
//   machinery — wrong shape for a build gate, right shape for a
//   PR-review helper. Future `daslib/sqlite_migrate_lint` (or similar).
//
// Documented limitations (escape hatches inline in tut 32):
//
// • LONG-RUNNING BACKFILLS. A migration that does
//   `UPDATE big_table …` over 10M rows holds the write-lock for
//   the body's transaction duration, AND replays on failure (since
//   the whole call is one txn). Escape: keep long backfills in their
//   own `migrate_to_latest` invocation; chunk via raw SQL inside
//   the body; future `chunked_update` helper if demand surfaces.
//
// • MULTI-DATABASE / MULTI-ATTACH MIGRATIONS. Atomic across ATTACHed
//   databases not supported — raw SQL works inside one migration but
//   no cross-DB ordering.
//
// • ZERO-DOWNTIME / EXPAND-CONTRACT discipline. Pair every
//   destructive migration with a paired app-code release; document
//   the sequence out-of-band. The struct-as-partial-projection
//   property (see CLAUDE / API_MIGRATION conceptual model) makes
//   additive migrations free; destructive ones (DROP COLUMN, NOT
//   NULL without default) need operator coordination.
//
// • REPEATABLE MIGRATIONS (Flyway concept; re-runnable for views,
//   functions, seed data). MVP ships only versioned one-shot
//   migrations. Escape: put the "always current" bits into your
//   app's startup code outside the migration system.
//
// In short: MVP is ~900 lines of runtime + macro across three
// chunks (14a/14b/14c). Anything in this deferred list is its own
// project. If you hit one of these and it's blocking, open an issue
// with a concrete use case — that's the signal we use to prioritize
// the next `daslib/sqlite_migrate_*` module.
